---
description: TypeScript / JavaScript house conventions - apply when editing .ts/.tsx/.js/.jsx/.mjs/.cjs.
globs: "**/*.ts,**/*.tsx,**/*.js,**/*.jsx,**/*.mjs,**/*.cjs"
alwaysApply: false
---

When creating or editing TypeScript/JavaScript (`.ts` / `.tsx` / `.js` / `.jsx` / `.mjs` /
`.cjs`), follow the framework-agnostic baseline carried by the `typescript` skill
under `.cursor/skills/`: strict typing, module boundaries, async patterns, and JS+JSDoc.
Prefer these over ad-hoc style.

If the `typescript` skill is not loaded, hold the line on the highest-value rules: no `any`
and no `@ts-ignore` (use a typed model or `@ts-expect-error` with a reason), and `await`
every promise rather than leaving it floating.

This is guidance, auto-attached by glob (not a hard block). Angular files (`*.component.ts`
&c.) also match `angular-conventions.mdc`, so both rules attach together on those.
